Symmetry implies that $ \mathbf{H} $ goes around in circles, perpendicular to the cylinder axis, and can only vary with the radius: $ \mathbf{H} = H(r) \, \boldsymbol{\hat{\phi}} $. The free volume current density is $ \mathbf{J_f} = I/\pi a^2 $, and so the free current enclosed in a circle of radius $ s $ is

$$
I_{f,enc} = 
\begin{cases} 
I(s^2/a^2), & s < a, \\ 
I, & s > a. 
\end{cases}
\tag{7.3.1}
$$


This is equal to the line integral of $ \mathbf{H} $, which is $ 2\pi s H(s) $. Hence,

$$
H(s) = \frac{I}{2\pi s}
\begin{cases} 
s^2/a^2, & s < a, \\ 
1, & s > a. 
\end{cases}
\tag{7.3.2}
$$


The magnetic field $ \mathbf{B} $ is $ \mathbf{B} = \mu \mathbf{H} = \mu H \boldsymbol{\hat{\phi}} $:

$$
B(s) = \frac{\mu_0 I}{2\pi s}
\begin{cases} 
(1+\chi_m) s^2/a^2, & s < a, \\ 
1, & s > a. 
\end{cases}
\tag{7.3.3}
$$


The bound current density is related to the free current density via

$$
\mathbf{J_b} = \nabla \times \mathbf{M} = \nabla \times (\chi_m \mathbf{H}) = \chi_m \mathbf{J_f}.
\tag{7.3.4}
$$


Since the free current density is $ \mathbf{J_f} = I/\pi a^2 $, we have

$$
\mathbf{J_b} = \chi_m I/\pi a^2 
\tag{7.3.5}
$$


The surface current density is

$$
\mathbf{K_b} = \mathbf{M} \times \mathbf{\hat{n}} = \chi_m \mathbf{H} \times \mathbf{\hat{r}} = -\chi_m I/2\pi a.
\tag{7.3.6}
$$


The net bound current vanishes. I suppose this makes sense, or else we would be getting more or less current out one end than we put in the other end!

$$
I_b = \pi a^2 J_b + 2\pi a K_b = 0.
\tag{7.3.7}
$$

